   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6dfeab9b-84b1-4b3d-833d-d1ccfaac7a3a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Numerical Solutions of Differential Equations"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "947046c9-6500-4af8-b60a-fb7c4ff05120",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "When solving a differential equation numerically, we distinguish between two fundamental types of problems:\n",
    "\n",
    "* **Initial Value Problems (IVP):** All boundary conditions are given at a single, specific point in time (typically $t=0$). These conditions include the initial position/value and the derivative(s) of the function at that exact starting point.\n",
    "* **Boundary Value Problems (BVP):** The conditions are split between different points in the domain, typically specifying the values at the very first and the very last points (the boundaries), without providing the derivative at the starting point.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each of these types is uniquely suited to model different natural phenomena:\n",
    "* **IVPs** are ideal for modeling **dynamic systems** that evolve and progress over time (e.g., satellite trajectories, planetary orbits, or projectile motion).\n",
    "* **BVPs** are typically used to describe **systems in spatial or structural equilibrium** (e.g., potential fields, steady-state heat conduction, or the deflection of structural beams under a load)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "666564cf-f823-42a8-b325-2269b738f1fc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## The Shooting Method"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "df11e33d-c34d-4e98-83c2-9e80fa2e6134",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To solve **Initial Value Problems (IVPs)**, computers utilize sequential \"marching methods\" that advance the solution step-by-step. These include Euler's method, Runge-Kutta methods (such as the famous $RK4$), Multi-step methods (such as Adams-Bashforth) and The Leapfrog method.\n",
    "\n",
    "Conversely, **Boundary Value Problems (BVPs)** are inherently more complex to solve because it is impossible to simply march forward from the beginning without having complete information at the starting point. \n",
    "Today, we will focus on a method that **transforms a BVP into an IVP**, making it highly efficient."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "46c57b90-3183-4859-bc99-b1d7e515a653",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To see how this is done, let us take an example of a simple pendulum with friction (damping). The equation is:\n",
    "$$\\ddot{\\theta} + b\\dot{\\theta} + \\frac{g}{L}\\sin(\\theta) = 0$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cd68231e-c0c6-4a1b-b884-b811eee44cbb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We have the first and last positions, but we do not have the velocity there. This is not enough.\n",
    "What we will do:\n",
    "- Check the velocities at each time from t=0 to t=5\n",
    "- Compare the numerical result we obtained, theta_final, to the expected result, theta_target, as a sort of error calculation.\n",
    "- The goal—to reach zero error! This is how we will know that the algorithm we wrote is correct."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "37ac5ec6-a6c8-41d3-8e8d-21a719a62243",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def pendulum_ode_system(t, state):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    ODE system for a simple pendulum with damping (friction):\n",
    "    u1 = theta (angular displacement in radians)\n",
    "    u2 = omega (angular velocity in radians per second)\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    theta, omega = state\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Physical parameters\n",
    "    g = 9.81  # Acceleration due to gravity (m/s^2)\n",
    "    L = 2.0   # Length of the pendulum string (m)\n",
    "    b = 0.5   # Damping (friction) coefficient (1/s)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Calculate the first derivatives\n",
    "    dtheta_dt = omega  # First derivative of position: d(theta)/dt = omega\n",
    "    domega_dt = -b * omega - (g / L) * np.sin(theta)  # First derivative of velocity (from the pendulum equation)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Return the derivatives as a NumPy array for the IVP solver\n",
    "    return np.array([dtheta_dt, domega_dt])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "be410c39-6e03-407e-9542-cf110ea8fc35",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We also have our RK4 method:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "5f580c1e-a1fc-41f3-850f-a7541ef5724c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def rk4_step(x, y, h, func):\n",
    "    k1 = func(x,y)\n",
    "    .....\n",
    "    return y + (h / 6.0) * (k1 + 2.0 * k2 + 2.0 * k3 + k4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5f4a76f3-e54d-47ee-9392-57de48322449",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And our IVP for an initial guess w_guess will look like this -"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "4ed2bb82-0cc8-4105-8697-870e887d2dcb",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def run_ivp_simulation(w_guess, t_pts, h):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    y_pts = np.zeros((len(x_pts), 2)) # to save both (theta, omega)\n",
    "    y_pts[0] = [1.0, w_guess]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for i in range(len(t_pts) - 1):\n",
    "        y_pts[i + 1] = rk4_step(t_pts[i], y_pts[i], h, pendulum_ode_system) \n",
    "        # y[i] is actually *two* values that goes into rk4_step\n",
    "\n",
    "    return y_pts[:, 0]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9253e3a6-b6d3-4266-b988-e9550bf770b2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, we want a function that connects all of these functions together—and stops the execution when the desired tolerance is reached. This is achieved using the **Secant Method**, which you will implement at home. Note that this method requires two initial guesses that are different from each other:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "b6c5a855-3110-4811-9345-cf683cfaec6c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def shooting_solver(t_start, t_end, target_value, h, tol=1e-6):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Solves the Boundary Value Problem (BVP) for the pendulum using the Shooting Method and Secant Method.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    # Generate the time domain vector\n",
    "    t_pts = np.arange(t_start, t_end + h / 2, h)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # --- Step A: Two initial shots (arbitrary guesses for the initial velocity) ---\n",
    "    w0 = 0.0   # Guess 1: Release the pendulum from rest\n",
    "    w1 = -2.0  # Guess 2: Push the pendulum hard to the left\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Shot 1: Run simulation and calculate error at the boundary (t=5)\n",
    "    theta_sim0 = run_ivp_simulation(w0, t_pts, h)\n",
    "    err0 = theta_sim0[-1] - target_value\n",
    "    print(f\"Guess 1: w = {w0:6.2f} -> Angle at end = {theta_sim0[-1]:7.2f} rad (Error = {err0:7.2f})\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Shot 2: Run simulation and calculate error at the boundary (t=5)\n",
    "    theta_sim1 = run_ivp_simulation(w1, t_pts, h)\n",
    "    err1 = theta_sim1[-1] - target_value\n",
    "    print(f\"Guess 2: w = {w1:6.2f} -> Angle at end = {theta_sim1[-1]:7.2f} rad (Error = {err1:7.2f})\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # --- Step B: Iterative Correction Loop (Secant Method) ---\n",
    "    _\n",
    "    return t_pts, theta_sim1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "18a69870-e72d-4cdb-acc4-b3fa7103e5c7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The use of the Secant Method is necessary here—in Newton-Raphson, we assume that we have an analytical formula for the derivative. In our case, we do not have a formula for the derivative; we only get it after a full run of RK4. Therefore, the Secant Method is used, which approximates the derivative by using our two previous \"shots.\""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "048dff80-f017-42e1-a0f0-262ee81c2937",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if __name__ == \"__main__\":\n",
    "    t_s, t_e = 0.0, 5.0  \n",
    "    theta_target = 0.0 # this is the location at t=5 - our target!\n",
    "    step_size = 0.05"
    "   ....."
   ]
  }
